1.BUG, unregistering and reregistering backend still displays that particular backend as unhealthy.
2.Periodic health checks
3.Every few seconds, attempt to connect to unhealthy backends and mark them healthy if they respond.
4.Metrics
Print or expose:
active_sessions
registered_backends
healthy_backends
total_connections
backend_failures
bytes_proxied
Config file
Support both:
./lb backends.conf
5.Non-blocking sockets
6.Make client/backend sockets non-blocking so one slow connection cannot freeze the whole load balancer.
7. Fix partial reads/writes
8. Right now you may assume recv()/send() transfers everything. Real TCP does not guarantee that. Add per-session buffers:
client_to_backend_buf
backend_to_client_buf
Better session cleanup
9. When a backend dies, remove every session using that backend, not just one fd.
10. Load-balancing policy
11. Add something beyond round-robin:
round_robin
least_connections
random
healthy_only
Config file
Instead of hardcoded ports:
listen_port=8080
metrics_port=9090
backend=127.0.0.1:9001
backend=127.0.0.1:9002
backend=127.0.0.1:9003
12. Tests
- round-robin test
- unhealthy backend skipped
- backend recovery test
- multiple concurrent clients
- metrics endpoint returns expected values
Switch from poll to epoll

5. Performance tests
After your poll() version works, build an epoll version. That becomes a real systems project.
